column169: Upon receipt at the Federal Express destination station in Spokane, WA, station employees observed a very strong, stringent odor and visual evidence of a grey substance that had leaked from a shrink-wrapped non-specification fiberboard box. Further investigation showed the box contained two 3.78L cans of 100713 – Evercoat FeatherFill G2 Premium Polyester Primer Surfacer. Per the SDS document associated with the product, this commodity is classified as Class 3 dangerous goods, specifically UN3269, Polyester Resin Kit. There were no Dangerous Goods markings or labels on the package, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to contain the shipment in a salvage drum and hold it pending further instructions regarding disposition.

On July 1, 2025, one (1) 55-gallon drum of NA1993 was forked and released approximately seven (7) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Green for Life (GFL) to remediate the site. The crew utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the trailer and dock floor. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged drum of product was placed in one (1) 85-gallon ocerpack.

On July 10, 2025, thirty-one (31) 1-gallon jugs of UN2817 fell off the load table and released approximately four (4) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GMES) to remediate the site. The 31 damaged pails were placed into two (2) 55-gallon drums. GMES personnel deployed granular absorbents and a neutralizing agent to the impacted area and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents, damaged boxes, PPE, and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum.

ABF Operation Supervisor states that they opened up trailer 504931 in dock door 34 and found a box of UN1993, FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (CONTAINS PETROLEUM DISTILLATES ISOPROPANOL), 3, PG II that had become crushed from load stacked on top of it during transit. ABF Supervisor states that none of it hit the ground. Safety contacted CURA and they're dispatching someone on emergency response to service the spill. Three (3) 1-gallon metal pails of UN1993, Flamm able liquid, n.o.s. (Contains Petroleum Distillates; Isopropanol) Sea Foam Motor Treatment (SF-128) were damaged and collectively released a total of 2-cups of product (Each 1-gallon pail contained 16-cups worth of product). All photos have been uploaded and we appreciate the opportunity to assist, thank you!~

ABF Supervisor states that none of it hit the yard. Safety c ontacted CURA and they're dispatching a cleanup crew on emergency response to the location. Following a site assessment, PES personnel collected seven (7) damaged five-gallon pails of UN1133 for disposal. Crews then utilized hand tools to collect the dried product on impacted dock floor. PES personn el then utilized absorbent pads and a cleaning agent to collect any residual product on adjacent freight. The undamaged freight was re-stacked and secured for normal transport. All UN1133 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum and all damaged UN1133 pails were co ntainerized in three (3) 55-gallon drums and ABF personnel took possession of the waste for terminal disposal. PES personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized.

column169: The warehouse coordinator at Veolia's ten day intransit facility in Richmond, VA unloaded pharmaceutical boxes from a Veolia service truck. He shrink wrapped them to a pallet and placed them on another Veolia trailer until the outbound shipment trailer was available. As he attempted to move the pallet off the trailer, the boxes shifted and fell to the floor. The weight of the boxes caused one of the box lids to become unsealed and it is estimated that 4 ounces leaked from the container onto the concrete warehouse floor. The container was quickly uprighted and resealed. The spill was cleaned up immediately. The container was repackaged with the spill cleanup material for transport.
column170: Veolia has hired a contractor (Southeastern Truck and Trailer) to adjust the tandem axle on the Veolia trailer. This will reduce the height difference between the trailer and the loading dock and will enable a smoother transition in and out of the trailer on the dock, limiting the risk of bouncing containers on a pallet.   Further investigation also revealed the boxes were not sufficiently secured with shrink wrap to the pallet. This issue has been addressed with the employee involved. In the future, he will verify that sufficient wrapping has been used to prevent shifting or moving of the containers on a pallet.

column169: on 7-1-2025, at 2350 hours JohnVergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, was called by the WLE Chief Dispatcher about car GBRX that was reported leaking by the crew who brought it into the yard after picking it up from a local business.  The crew reported fumes coming from the top of the tank car. There was no exposure to employees from the fumes. John Vergis arrived @0010 hrs. to find it leaking from the Liquid line on top the car.  The car was fuming heavily.  John called the Summit County Spill Line at 0012hrs. to make a report but had to leave a message and his called not returned.  The Ohio EPA was called at 0115 and a report made with Report #2507EPA0001093 given.  Enviroserve was called to make the repair to the car at 0059hrs.  When they arrived and assessed the situation, it was determined that the blind flange on the liquid line was not properly tightened, causing the leak.  The flange was torqued to the proper specs and the leak stopped.  The inside of the housing was cleaned with water and then released back into transportation at 0350 hrs. On July 3, 2025 at 2300 hrs., the same car was found in the WLE Hartland Yard in Collins, OH leaking again from the same fitting.  Enviroserve was called out again, and it was found that the top flange on the liquid line had a double flat gasket installed.  This is where the fitting was leaking.  This double gasket was not noticed the first time.  When the flange was removed, it was found that both gaskets were defective and that it was possible the shipper tried making one good gasket out of two.  John Vergis called the shipper and let them know of the situation.  The shipper sent out technicians to replace the bad gaskets with one new one.  The car was then released back into transportation.

column169: ABF Supervisor states that they opened up trailer 500092 in dock door 205 when they found a 50LB bag of UN3190, SELF - HEATING SOLID, INORGANIC, N.O. S. (FERROSO FERRIC OXIDE), 4.2, PG II that had become punctured due to abrasion from another piece of freight and not having an enough duntage around it. ABF Supervisor states that none of it had spilled out onto the yard. ABF Supervisor states that this was caused by improper loading at the previous terminal. Safety advised to close the trailer until a cleaning crew arrives on scene. Safety contacted CURA and they're dispatching a cleaning crew on emergency response to service the spill. ABF advised Supervisor to send photos to Safety. A crew from TLE arrived on-site and donned the appropriate level of personal protective equipment (PPE). Following a site assessment, TLE personnel noted two (2) damaged 50-pound boxes of UN3190 with approxi mately five (5) pounds of product released to the trailer floor. An on-site ABF forklift was utilized to offload all cargo from the trailer for better access to the spill. All cargo was staged onto poly sheeting for inspection and wiped down to remove any residual product. The undamaged cargo was re -palletized for continued processing and shipping. TLE personnel utilized a HEPA vacuum and hand tools to collect all free-standing products from the impacted area. TLE personnel utilized a degreasing agent and absorbent pads to wipe down the area to ensure thorough cleaning. The contents of the vac uum, all impacted material, and damaged bags were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drums for disposal purposes. The drums were properly labeled, and the waste was staged on-site for further management. After receiving approval from on-site ABF representative, Corey Campbell, TLE pe rsonnel noted no further actions required and crews demobilized.

column169: A trailer was discovered to be leaking black paint onto the yard. The trailer was in a set on the outbound line. The operations supervisor advised that the trailer has not been opened so the cause of the spill and how much spilled and the container capacity are all unknown. Safety advised that CURA would be contacted for remediation and will determine unknowns. A crew with FCE arrived onsite and donned the appropriate level of personal protective equipment (PPE). Following a site assessment, FCE personnel observed 27 damaged one (1) gallon pails of UN1263 with approximately fifteen (15) gallon s of product released to the trailer floor, cardboard box, neighboring cargo, and trailer exterior. Crews deployed granular absorbents to solidify any free standing product. Crews deployed additional granular absorbents and absorbent pads to collect any residual product during unloading. Impacted ne ighboring cargo was collected and staged onsite for further management. Crews utilized a pressure washer and multiple cleaning agents to remove residual material, and deployed boom to collect any rinsate. However, no product could be removed from the trailer floor during pressure washing.All 27 dama ged units of UN1263 were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly lined metal drum. Spent PPE, spent boom, and spent absorbents and pads were collected and containerized into three (3) additional 55-gallon poly lined metal drums. All four (4) drums of generated waste were properly lab eled and staged onsite for further management. After receiving approval from onsite ABF representative, Mr. Chad, FCE personnel noted no further action was required and crews demobilized.

column169: Dayton Freight personnel observed approximately seven (7) gallons of material released from two (2) 5-gallon metal pails due to unknown reasons that resulted in the pails leaking. The released material impacted the trailer floor. Dayton Freight personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted area and gathered the spent material and containerized it into two (2) 5-gallon poly drums. One (1) 35-gallon poly drum was used to containerize the damaged containers. The generated waste was staged onsite at the terminal in a secure location. The generated waste will remain onsite for Dayton Freight’s contracted hazardous waste vendor to coordinate disposal.

column169: Shane Hilsabeck, Operations Supervisor, called Safety to report a spill of UN1170, Ethanol, Class 3, PG II in trailer 554322 and on the dock near Door 3. Shane stated that the drum was punctured by a forklift operator while unloading the skid. The forklift fork went under the skid and struck the dru m, creating a puncture that caused approximately 20 gallons of ethanol to leak onto the dock floor. The spill has been contained. Shane reported that the drum was placed on top of a container to contain the leak and that Safety was notified. He also requested a cleaning crew to assist with the clean up. Crews deployed absorbent pads to the UN1170-impacted containment skid to absorb and remove all released material. One (1) damaged 55-gallon drum of UN1170 was patched and overpacked into one (1) 85-gallon overpack drum. All spent absorbents, PPE, and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. All collected waste was staged onsite for future transport and disposal by CES. Crews received site approval from Shane Hilsabeck, secured the scene, and demobilized.

column169: On July 6, 2025, two (2) 1-gallon jugs of SaniDate 5.0 were damaged due to a load shift and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. column169: As the freight was being unloaded at the origin terminal, one of the drums was punctured accidentally by a forklift blade. The drum was immediately secured to prevent further release of material and the released material was absorbed and set aside for proper disposal. column170: This incident could have been prevented had the forklift operator been more aware of their fork location. The employee involved in this incident was counselled per company policy. This incident may be used in future dock safety topics to demonstrate the importance of following proper forklift operating procedures.

column169: At approximately 14:45 on 7/8/2025, FedEx Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Package Research and Recovery station in Olive Branch, MS concerning a smoking package.  An employee noticed the package initially due to a popping/explsosive sound which then released smoke with slight burning to the fibreboard box. The package did not fully catch fire and was contained and put into a salvage package with water to contain any potential fire.  The package contained small vehicle tracking devices containing non-rechargeable lithium batteries.  The shipment arrived at the overgoods station with no tracking label, so no shipper or recipient information is available, however system restrictions for this incident require shipper info to be entered.  Zip 38654 was used to suffice the shipper postal code, however "uknown" was listed for all other fields concerning the shipper since none is avialable on the package..  The shipment was held pending dispostion from Dangerous Goods Administration.

column169: The trailer was picked up as a shipper load and count.  Upon arriving at our facility, the dockworker noticed several pallets tipped over including the pallet with the spill.  Immediate action was taken to upright the drum and stop the leak.  Roughly 8oz of liquid seeped from the closure.  The drum was placed in an overpack container in preparation for disposition or reuse after thoroughly cleaning the drum.  All spilled fluid was neutralized and swept up using absorbents.
column170: Proper load securement by both the driver or shipper could have prevented this.  This event will be reviewed thoroughly to determine if the driver is culpable and if disciplinary action is warranted.

column169: Other freight was double stacked on top of the drums.  While in transit, the pallet shifted slightly causing the end of the pallet to hang over the drums. As the dock worker was attempting to unload the shifted pallet, he punctured the drum.  Leadership was immediately notified and hazwoper trained personnel tipped the drum to its side to stop the leak.  The drum was patched with putty and placed in an overpack container.  All leaked material was contained and cleaned up with absorbents.  All contaminated clean up materials were packed into a separate overpack container in preparation for disposition.
column170: Proper load securement and use of dunnage should have been practiced by the driver.  Safer unloading techniques should be practiced by the dock worker.  Disciplinary action will be taken for this event.

column169: David Vest, 084 Operations Supervisor, contacted Safety regarding a UN1263 spill on the rear of the trailer. David Vest advised a pallet sitting on top of the damaged freight, crushing a carton on the rear of the trailer. David Vest advised the spill has leaked onto other cartons on the pallet. David Vest stated the spill is contained to the trailer and the lip of the trailer. Safety advised David Vest to place absorbent pads down to contain the spill from striking the yard. Kailee Mason with CURA was contacted for remediation. Following a site assessment, HES personnel noted one (1) damaged cardboard box containing four (4) 1-gallon pails of UN1263, with approximately one (1) gallon of product released onto cardboard boxes, the trailer floor, and concrete beneath the trailer. Upon further inspection, crews confirmed that only one (1) of the 1-gallon pails was damaged. The one (1) damaged pail was placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal purposes. HES personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted surfaces and worked them in with hand tools. Absorbent pads and cleaners were used to remove any residual product. The undamaged cargo was repalletized for continued processing and shipping by the facility. All spent absorbents, impacted cardboard boxes, and UN1263-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal. The drums were properly labeled and staged on site for further management.

While doing a site walk at Veolia's ten day in transit facility in Westland, MI, a strong odor was noted. The Veolia team suspected the smell originated from trailer W18938 which had been brought over late Friday evening 1500 (7/11/25) and was on it's way to the disposal facility. After further investigation a wet stain was found along with a strong solvent aroma in the dock well of Dock 2. The stain in the dock well led directly to the storm drain which had the same strong odor. Determining the issue was related to the load, the driver was immediately contacted. The driver pulled over the van trailer at a rest-area to inspect the shipment. It was confirmed that there were no active leaks occurring. After inspecting the shipping papers and the load, only 4 containers were identified as containing liquid material (1 x 55 gallon drum and 3 x 5 gallon carboys). The driver inspected all 4 containers and overpacked the 1 55 gallon drum and 1 carboy. The 55 gallon drum was determined to be leaking. The carboy was overpacked as a proactive measure due to poor integrity of the container.   The State of Michigan was contacted through the PEAS system - and a report was filed with Michigan EGLE # 34083. Veolia employees at the Westland site cleaned any potential contaminants from the storm drain and dock area. The work included using floor dry on the hard surfaces and vacuuming out any residual in the storm drain and cleaning the surfaces inside. A sample of the drain will be pulled and sent for analytical testing. All clean up materials will be disposed of properly.
column170: The truck dock storm drain was left uncovered while a vehicle was in the dock. This is against normal procedure. Additionally, hazmat containers were not examined for integrity. It is a requirement of the pre-trip procedure to ensure that materials being prepared for transport have the structural integrity to be safely transported. In this situation, the drum should have been overpacked when it was loaded onto the truck.

column169: 042/CAR advised trailer 84077 arrived leaking onto the yard (no drains or waterways). ABF advised the freight was double stacked with no blocking or bracing. Cura was called to send out a crew to remediate the spill. Crews donned the appropriate PPE and identified the estimated one half (0.5) gallon release of product to the trailer floor and pavement below. FCE personnel downstacked the pallet and observed one (1) damaged 5-gallon pail of Novato Automatic Dish Detergent (UN3266) had a lid that sprang loose due to a load shift. Once the lid was secured, crews tested the pail to see if any further product would release, and the pail was found to be secured. Crews were instructed to remediate the freight for further shipment and processing, so FCE personnel utilized rags and sodium-bicarbonate solution to wipe down the pail then restacked all undamaged freight for further shipment and processing. The impacted trailer floor and pavement were neutralized with sodium bicarbonate, and the neutralized product was collected with hand tools. One (1) 55-gallon drum that contained the neutralized product and any cleanup debris was generated as waste, labeled as non-hazardous, and staged in the terminal's waste holding room. With approval of the site contact, Kevin Scheidler, crews secured the scene and demobilized.

column169: On July 3, 2025, due to a load shift, one (1) 5-gallon pail of Urethane Reducer Slow was crushed and released four (4) gallons of product, thirteen (13) 1-gallon pails of System 20 High Build Primer Gray released thirteen (13) gallons of product, and one (1) 1-gallon pail of Economy Lacquer Thinner released approximately one-half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the spill-impacted trailer floor and pavement below the trailer and swept them in with hand tools. All spent granular absorbents, PPE, and debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged pails of product were containerized in three (3) 55-gallon drums.

column169: Mike Cheadle, 064 Operations Supervisor, contacted Safety regarding a paint related spill on the trailer floor. Mike Cheadle advised the origin had the box double stacked and it appears the box shifted in transit causing the pallet to hang in midair resulting in the spill. Mike Cheadle stated he wip ed off the spill on the seal of the trailer door and the rim of the trailer with absorbent pads. Mike Cheadle advised he placed the absorbent pads in a white savage drum near the trailer. Mike Cheadle advised the box is saturated. Safety advised Mike Cheadle that CURA is to be contacted on all hazar dous spills. Safety stated to stop cleanup and allow Safety to contact Cura. Mike Cheadle advised it appears the freight is no longer leaking. Mike Cheadle stated the freight is moved from the position it arrived to the ground of the trailer in the upright position.  TLE personnel collected five (5)  damaged 3-gallon containers of Absco Swedish Finish (UN 1263) and containerized them in one (1) 35-gallon drum. Crews then collected all UN 1263 impacted cardboard and pallets and containerized them in one (1) 55-gallon drum. TLE personnel utilized absorbent pads to remediate residual product on th e trailer floor. All UN 1263 impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum and one (1) 35-gallon drum and left on-site for future terminal disposal. TLE personnel noted no further action required on-site and crews demobilized. Following the corrective actions, no visual  or olfactory evidence of the UN 1263 could be observed at the site. Based on these results, it appears the corrective actions were successful, and no further action should be required.

column169: A Veolia employee was moving a 55 gallon 1A1 drum to the vehicle's lift gate with a drum cart. While on the lift gate, the drum was turned parallel to the incline instead of perpendicular. As a result, the drum fell back towards the incline of the lift and on to its side. After about 1 min. on its side, the drum sprang a leak at its top and spilled approximately .75 gal of dihydropyran. The material leaked out of a small crease in the lid of the drum. The crease was caused by the impact of the fall.
column170: Proper drum securement when using a drum cart and situational awareness were reviewed with the employees involved in the incident

column169: On July 17, 2025, one (1) 5-gallon jug of UN2922 was punctured by a nail and released approximately one-half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from ES+, LLC (ES+) to remediate the site. The crew neutralized the trailer with sodium bicarbonate and swept it in with hand tools. All impacted materials were containerized in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The damaged jug was containerized in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum.

column43: ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, NOT LESS THAN 50 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column169: On 07/01/2025 at approximately 1428, David Terry reported an undeclared dangerous good. The shipment consisted of a plastic container packaged in a fiberboard box. The commodity was identified as acetic acid solution with not less than 50% but not more than 80% acid, and it was not prepared in accordance with DOT HMR Regulations. Per the agent, this shipper has repeatedly attempted to ship this package, which lead to further inspection. The package is being held, pending DOT investigation. The shipper confirmed by provision of the safety data sheet, the shipment is not less than 50% acid, and is over the 1 liter limited quantity.
column170: Shipper has shipped this product many times; sometimes through USPS, and does not declare the product as a hazardous material.

column169: Swing door trailer arrived to 283 and when the doors were opened, a pallet that had not been properly strapped to the wall and had been leaning on the doors fell. EXE personnel arrived and assessed the site. VER personnel tightened the lid on the impacted jug. A nuetralizing agent was deployed to the exterior of the product as well as all impacted areas. VER personnel restacked all product and staged them onsite for f uture shipping. Absorbent pads were placed on the ground. All absorbents were placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum which was staged onsite for future disposal by CES personnel. Crews secured the scene and demobilized.

column169: Following the aircraft’s departure from OMA to VPS, a service-provider agent notified their leadership that a personal e-cigarette (UN3481) could not be located and was believed to have been left in the cargo compartment where they were working. Leadership immediately informed the Operations Control Center, which relayed the information to the Pilot-in-Command. Existing guidance in the General Operations Manual addresses only hazardous materials found “within the cabin,” leaving the PIC initially uncertain about the appropriate action that should be taken. As a precautionary measure, the PIC elected to divert the aircraft to XNA. Once the aircraft was grounded, a service agent was able to locate the device (UN3481) within the cargo space and remove it. There was no indication of damage to the AC. There was no photo taken at the time of identification. This was not intended to be a shipment of hazardous materials, and no shipper declaration was created.
column170: To prevent future ambiguity, the General Operations Manual will be updated to mirror the Hazardous Materials Manual, offering explicit procedures for in-flight hazardous materials incidents, irrespective of where on the aircraft they occur. This revision will ensure comprehensive, clear direction for addressing hazardous items throughout the aircraft. Additionally, the Station Operations Manual currently lacks clear guidance regarding items employees may carry while working on the flight line. We will initiate a review with the operations team to possibly enhance the manual, explicitly prohibiting hazardous materials—such as vape pens and other electronic cigarettes—by personnel in secure or sensitive operational areas.

column169: At 0900 hours on 7-16-2025, the WLE Rook Yard car inspector noticed tank car GATX 204236 leaking down the sides of the tank from the top of the car.  He called myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Office for the WLE.  When I arrived, I checked the manway bolts and found that all of them were less than tool tight with two of the bolts being able to be loosened by hand.  I opened the breadbox lid removing seal number 0774725 from the lid.  I then opened the Vapor valve to release any potential pressure and then opened the manway lid.  I removed old seal 0774724 from the manway lid.  The gasket appeared to be in Ok shape but I installed a new gasket anyway.  I then closed the manway lid and tightened the lid with the proper torque pattern.  I installed new seal number 0000228 on the manway lid and new seal number 0000227 on the breadbox lid.  I then had Specialized Professional Services come out of Washington, PA on July 18th to clean the asphalt off the sides and top of the car. I then released the car back into transportation.

column169: On July 10, 2025, at approximately 4:45PM, an OxyChem truck driver was completing a delivery of Perchloroethylene to Lion Oil in El Dorado, AR. Near the end of the offload, customer site personnel stopped offloading operations and explained that their storage tank was almost at full capacity and was adamant that the remaining amount of product be offloaded into a tote. The trailer was depressurized, hoses were cleared, and the line was disconnected from plant piping and placed into a tote by customer site personnel. Upon receiving instruction from customer site personnel, the driver slowly began to open the trailer valves to gravity unload the remainder of the product into a tote under zero pressure. During the process, the hose came out of the tote with approximately 5 gallons of product escaping to the ground. The driver immediately shut the trailer valves to stop the product release. The customer site personnel performed in-house cleanup with no injuries or environmental impact.
column170: Recommendations by OxyChem Tech Service group to the customer site will be needed. Recommendations will include ensuring that all product delivered to the site can fit into storage tanks to eliminate having to offload into a tote. Additional recommendation will be to have proper fittings and setup on-site for tote offloading if it needs to occur.
